    - m_Type: 0
      Title:
        m_Untranslated: 
      Text:
        m_Untranslated: "Using <b>Sampling Noise</b> indoors can sometimes cause
          leaking artifacts, as seen in the image above. \n\nThankfully, with the
          help of a Local <b> Probe Volumes</b> added to the Scene, we can force
          the <b>Probe Spacing</b> to be fixed within a certain zone, with no subdivision
          level. In this Scene, this results will result in the placement of probes
          at a fixed distance of 0.6m only. \n\nWith no subdivision levels in this
          particular area, more probes are created: the baking time and the amount
          of data on disk will thus slightly increase. However, it will prevent most
          lighting seams.\n\nTo reproduce the artifact seen in the image above, follow
          these steps:\n\n1. Add a Cube at <b>X:25.3 Y:2 Z:1.5</b>\n\n2. In the <i>Hierarchy</i>
          window select <b>Lighting</b> > <b>Probe Volumes</b> > <b>Probe Volume
          Local.</b>\n\nNotice that the range slider has its Min and Max value set
          at 0.6m, and that the _Fill Empty Space_ option is enabled.\n\n3. Disable the <b>Probe Volume Local</b> GameObject and save
          the scene.\n\n4. Click the <b>Generate Lighting</b> button at the bottom
          of the <i>Lighting</i> window to rebake the lighting.\n\nThe sampling artifact
          will appear on the Cube.\n\n5. Re-enable the <b>Probe Volume Local</b>
          GameObject and regenerate the lighting to fix the issue again."
